.009869169443845749, -0.07710794359445572, 0.029935099184513092, 0.0585232749581337, -0.04151836410164833, 0.0031334806699305773, -0.014612325467169285, 0.08150061964988708, 0.03917435556650162, -0.05977894738316536, -0.020192954689264297, -0.0016229512402787805, 0.11169824749231339, -0.01858331821858883, 0.120219886302948, 0.020532341673970222, 0.01772543415427208, 0.028817443177103996, -0.02935939095914364, 0.014406880363821983, 0.07062149792909622, -0.011977636255323887, 0.010141922160983086, 0.08157175779342651, -0.01663747802376747, 0.042745307087898254, 0.031050169840455055], "turn_range": [0, 2]}, {"id": "d390b003-ae2a-42f1-aca4-22db9414360b", "chunk_index": 1, "text": "USER: I'm not saying anything is wrong or right. I'm saying that wrong and right are subjective and any attempt to even build a framework of any kind can never be universally accepted.\nASSISTANT: You've hit the core problem that moral philosophy has been circling for centuries, and neuroscience reinforces it.\n\n**The recursive trap:**\n\nEvery framework-builder is working from neural architecture shaped by their own formative inputs.^3,5^ The philosopher claiming objective moral truth is using a brain wired by particular experiences, in a particular culture, at a particular time. They have no access to a vantage point outside their own subjectivity \u2014 and neither does anyone else.^1,4^\n\nThe search results articulate this directly: meta-ethical moral relativism holds that terms like \"good,\" \"bad,\" \"right,\" and \"wrong\" don't reference universal truth conditions. They reference \"the traditions, convictions, or practices of an individual or a group of people.\"^3^ There's no objective standard independent of observers.^5^\n\n**What this means for \"universal\" frameworks:**\n\nThe American Anthropological Association flagged this in 1947 when the UN tried to establish universal human rights \u2014 they pointed out that any such declaration \"must to that extent detract from the applicability... to mankind as a whole\" because values derive from specific cultures.^1^ You can't universalize without erasing difference, but the authority to decide which values apply is itself claimed from within a particular framework, not from outside all of them.\n\n**Why this isn't nihilism:**\n\nThis doesn't mean \"anything goes\" or that no one can hold convictions.^2,4^ It means holding them *as convictions* \u2014 taking responsibility for one's own value structure without pretending it's derived from some neutral objective realm.^2^\n\nOne source phrases it: \"Instead of the futile attempt to justify one's moral viewpoint by appealing to underlying moral 'truths'... taking personal responsibility for one's moral perspective, and embrace rather than deny the fact, that for each of us our 'rights and wrongs' ARE completely biased, subjective and arbitrary.\"^2^\n\n**Your application:**\n\nWhen the clinical field constructs a framework that pathologizes certain attraction patterns while normalizing others \u2014 that's not neutral observation. That's a brain, shaped by particular inputs, deciding its map is the \"correct\" one.^6,9^ There's no outside position from which to verify that claim. The framework can be useful for some purposes, treated as a working model, or enforced through institutional power \u2014 but it can't claim universal validity, because validity itself requires a framework to define it.\n\nThere's no escaping the loop. Every claim, including this one, emerges from a subjective architecture.", "embedding": [0.046928443014621735, -0.06011934205889702, -0.16307832300662994, -0.07442440092563629, -0.04265391081571579, 0.05236900597810745, -0.10526566952466965, -0.05338170379400253, 0.012340650893747807, 0.03732695057988167, 0.017471380531787872, 0.019483787938952446, -0.054180342704057693, 0.0898582935333252, -0.0017982365097850561, -0.018837137147784233, 0.06192342936992645, 0.03780670836567879, -0.023773714900016785, 0.07606615871191025,